Write a **Deliverables** section for this proposal.

This section is the contractual backbone of the proposal. It must be specific enough to prevent disputes about what was and wasn't in scope.

Project context:
- Description: {{ project_description }}
- Budget: {{ budget }}
- Timeline: {{ timeline }}
- Goals: {{ goals }}

Structure the deliverables into logical groups. For each group:

### [Group Name] (e.g. "Design Deliverables", "Development Deliverables", "Documentation")
List each concrete deliverable as a bullet with:
- **Deliverable name** — what it is
- Format/medium (e.g. Figma file, deployed web app, PDF report, GitHub repository)
- Acceptance criteria (1 sentence: how you both know it's done)

Groups to consider (include only those relevant to this project):
- **Strategy & Discovery** — research outputs, technical spec, architecture diagrams
- **Design** — wireframes, mockups, design system, prototypes
- **Software / Development** — application(s), APIs, admin panels, integrations
- **Data & Reporting** — dashboards, exports, analytics setup
- **Infrastructure** — deployment pipelines, hosting configuration, monitoring setup
- **Documentation** — user guides, API docs, runbooks, training materials
- **Quality Assurance** — test reports, performance benchmarks
- **Handover** — source code ownership, credentials, walkthrough sessions

End with a short **"Not in Scope"** subsection listing 3–5 things explicitly excluded, to prevent future disputes.

Be concrete. Vague deliverables ("a working website") cause more client disputes than anything else.
